hands_on_practices.solution:
We have 
$$f(x,y,z)=z^2\arctan\!\bigl(\tfrac{x}{y}\bigr)\,. $$
Compute the gradient components. Let $\theta=\arctan(x/y)$. Then
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}
=z^2\frac{d\theta}{dx}
=z^2\frac{1}{1+(x/y)^2}\frac{1}{y}
=\frac{z^2y}{x^2+y^2},$$
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}
=z^2\frac{d\theta}{dy}
=z^2\frac{1}{1+(x/y)^2}\Bigl(-\frac{x}{y^2}\Bigr)
=-\frac{z^2x}{x^2+y^2},$$
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}
=2z\,\arctan\!\bigl(\tfrac{x}{y}\bigr).$$
At $P_0=(1,1,2)$ we have $x^2+y^2=2$ and $\arctan(1)=\pi/4$, so
$$\nabla f(P_0)=\bigl(2,\,-2,\;\pi\bigr).$$
The given direction vector is $\mathbf v=(1,-1,1)$, whose unit vector is
$$\mathbf u=\frac{1}{\sqrt3}(1,-1,1).$$
Hence the directional derivative is
$$D_{\mathbf u}f(P_0)
=\nabla f(P_0)\cdot\mathbf u
=\frac{2\cdot1+(-2)\cdot(-1)+\pi\cdot1}{\sqrt3}
=\frac{4+\pi}{\sqrt3}\,. $$
